a great investment,

00:05:00.810 --> 00:05:03.270
if, for example, you
have a private company?

00:05:03.270 --> 00:05:06.420
You can't just say, well, the
price of the stock went up.

00:05:06.420 --> 00:05:10.200
If it's private, there's no
public share price disclosure.

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:12.089
So you know, the
simple way to describe

00:05:12.089 --> 00:05:14.130
it is if the pile of money
at the end of the year

00:05:14.130 --> 00:05:15.963
is bigger than at the
beginning of the year,

00:05:15.963 --> 00:05:18.000
you know it's been successful.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:24.390
But if you had a business that
had so much opportunity to grow

00:05:24.390 --> 00:05:26.430
that you invested
all the free cash,

00:05:26.430 --> 00:05:29.013
and so you didn't have a pile
of money at the end of the year,

00:05:29.013 --> 00:05:31.125
you invested it in
initiatives to grow,

00:05:31.125 --> 00:05:33.687
you have to go to your
accountant, or your bookkeeper,

00:05:33.687 --> 00:05:35.520
or go to your CFO, or
whatever, and he says,

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:38.290
well, this is what your value
was at the end of last year,

00:05:38.290 --> 00:05:40.920
and this is what your value
is at the end of this year.

00:05:40.920 --> 00:05:43.270
And that's how you know if
a business is successful.

00:05:43.270 --> 00:05:44.790
And it's a really
important idea,

00:05:44.790 --> 00:05:47.820
because it just brings you back
to the simple issue of rate

00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:49.050
of return.

00:05:49.050 --> 00:05:52.200
And so, not only how much has
it gone up, but on an annualized

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:55.540
basis, and then you have
things you can compare it to.

00:05:58.140 --> 00:06:02.249
So in that issue
about investors,

00:06:02.249 --> 00:06:04.290
what makes a great investor,
or one of the things

00:06:04.290 --> 00:06:07.320
you ask yourself, do
you take undue risks?

00:06:07.320 --> 00:06:09.420
How do you define the risks?

00:06:09.420 --> 00:06:10.622
How do you tell?

00:06:10.622 --> 00:06:12.413
Have you lost a
significant amount of money

00:06:12.413 --> 00:06:13.680
in an investment.

00:06:13.680 --> 00:06:15.270
Why do you think
you've done that?

00:06:15.270 --> 00:06:20.950
All of these are important as we
develop our skill as investors.

00:06:20.950 --> 00:06:26.220
And as I said, I had the
advantage of a clean canvas.

00:06:26.220 --> 00:06:29.840
That is, I knew nothing when
I came into the business.

00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:32.730
And I worked for a firm
that, when I joined it

00:06:32.730 --> 00:06:36.270
in July of 1968, was
the most important

00:06:36.270 --> 00:06:39.090
financial intermediary
in Washington, DC.

00:06:39.090 --> 00:06:40.730
It had financed Geico.

00:06:40.730 --> 00:06:42.030
It had financed Marriott.

00:06:42.030 --> 00:06:44.520
It financed all
the other companies

00:06:44.520 --> 00:06:46.680
that were public in
the Washington area.

00:06:46.680 --> 00:06:49.034
And the world was
changing rapidly,

00:06:49.034 --> 00:06:51.450
as it related to the investment
business and the brokerage

00:06:51.450 --> 00:06:54.540
business in the late
'60s and early '70s.

00:06:54.540 --> 00:06:56.760
And this firm
wasn't particularly

00:06:56.760 --> 00:07:00.480
well-suited to deal with that,
but they were financially very

00:07:00.480 --> 00:07:00.990
strong.

00:07:00.990 --> 00:07:03.180
And it gave me an
opportunity, as I

00:07:03.180 --> 00:07:06.390
say, to follow my own
nose in that business.

00:07:06.390 --> 00:07:08.470
And that's how it
all comes about.

00:07:08.470 --> 00:07:10.560
So when we get to
the piece about,

00:07:10.560 --> 00:07:12.660
well, what makes a
great investment,

00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:15.750
I go back to the issue
of rate of return.

00:07:15.750 --> 00:07:18.780
Sometimes, a great investment
might be simply described

00:07:18.780 --> 00:07:20.870
as, well, it met my goal.

00:07:20.870 --> 00:07:22.590
That doesn't tell you anything.

00:07:22.590 --> 00:07:26.190
Rate of return, we
say in our firm,

00:07:26.190 --> 00:07:29.770
is the bottom line
of all investing,

00:07:29.770 --> 00:07:33.280
and that's a really important
thing to think about.

00:07:33.280 --> 00:07:41.700
And so Saurabh and I were
talking before this chat

00:07:41.700 --> 00:07:47.080
today about businesses
that compound at 8% or 9%.

00:07:47.080 --> 00:07:50.610
And I said, you know, 8% or
9%, when you compare it to a 1

00:07:50.610 --> 00:07:54.150
and 1/2% interest rate on the
10-year is pretty attractive.

00:07:54.150 --> 00:07:57.930
And everything's relative,
but I think rate of return

00:07:57.930 --> 00:08:00.660
is hugely important.

00:08:00.660 --> 00:08:04.500
And so then I went
to discover what

00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:07.830
the historical rates of return
were in all different asset

00:08:07.830 --> 00:08:12.030
categories-- stocks, bonds,
art, real estate, oil

00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:16.570
and gas, collectibles,
fancy cars, you name it.

00:08:16.570 --> 00:08:19.600
And when I was looking at this
over, maybe, 70 years now,

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:22.350
or a 100 years, or
something like that,

00:08:22.350 --> 00:08:28.680
the data indicates that public
companies in the United States

00:08:28.680 --> 00:08:33.690
have compounded at roughly
between 9% and 10% a year.

00:08:33.690 --> 00:08:36.830
And that's better than all
other asset categories,

00:08:36.830 --> 00:08:39.360
and it's unleveraged.

00:08:39.360 --> 00:08:44.700
And so that causes me
to ask another question,

00:08:44.700 --> 00:08:48.030
and that other question
is, well, why is that so?

00:08:48.030 --> 00:08:51.390
Why isn't it 3% or
why isn't it 16%?

00:08:51.390 --> 00:08:56.820
And I'm not terribly
mathematically inclined,

00:08:56.820 --> 00:09:00.480
and so I use the term
that it correlates,

00:09:00.480 --> 00:09:03.090
but I don't do that with
a mathematical background.

00:09:03.090 --> 00:09:09.720
I'm just saying I observe that
that 9%, 10%, not too precise,

00:09:09.720 --> 00:09:13.650
is it approximates what
these companies are earning

00:09:13.650 --> 00:09:15.050
on the shareholders' capital.

00:09:15.050 --> 00:09:18.525
That is, we refer
to it simply as ROE.

00:09:18.525 --> 00:09:21.090
We look a little
bit more in depth,

00:09:21.090 --> 00:09:23.820
we're talking about
free cash flow return,

00:09:23.820 --> 00:09:25.594
you know, subtracting
maintenance, CAPEX,

00:09:25.594 --> 00:09:27.510
and that sort of stuff
on the owner's capital,

00:09:27.510 --> 00:09:29.640
the capital employed.

00:09:29.640 --> 00:09:35.940
And so I go from there
to posit the following.

00:09:35.940 --> 00:09:41.430
Our return in an asset
will approximate the ROE

00:09:41.430 --> 00:09:46.410
over a period of years,
given constant valuation

00:09:46.410 --> 00:09:51.010
and given the absence
of any distributions.

00:09:51.010 --> 00:09:53.820
So you all look up at me
and you say, well, you fool.

00:09:53.820 --> 00:09:56.700
Everybody knows you don't have a
constant valuation in the stock

00:09:56.700 --> 00:09:58.000
market.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:02.640
So we just work very hard to
have an attractive valuation

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:03.250
at the start.

00:10:03.250 --> 00:10:06.600
And you know, as it relates
to compounding your capital,

00:10:06.600 --> 00:10:09.480
your opportunity for a
higher rate of compounding

00:10:09.480 --> 00:10:11.880
is enhanced by a lower
valuation at the start.

00:10:11.880 --> 00:10:14.810
I mean, it's just real simple.

00:10:14.810 --> 00:10:18.990
And I have a little bit of
an arithmetic proof of that,

00:10:18.990 --> 00:10:20.820
if you're interested.

00:10:20.820 --> 00:10:26.010
You take a $10 stock with a $5
book and $1 worth of earnings.

00:10:26.010 --> 00:10:29.220
So it's 10 times earnings,
it's 2 times book,

00:10:29.220 --> 00:10:31.830
and it's at 20% ROE.

00:10:31.830 --> 00:10:35.640
And you apply that
to the company

00:10:35.640 --> 00:10:37.410
and see what happens
to the stock price.

00:10:37.410 --> 00:10:39.900
So you add that dollar's
worth to that 20% ROE,

00:10:39.900 --> 00:10:44.220
you add that dollar to the
$5, you have a $6 book.

00:10:44.220 --> 00:10:46.980
Two times book is 12.

00:10:46.980 --> 00:10:50.370
You have a 10 times earnings.

00:10:50.370 --> 00:10:52.910
By the way, it's
$1.20 in earnings now,

00:10:52.910 --> 00:10:54.330
10 times earnings is 12.

00:10:54.330 --> 00:10:57.030
So the stock price
moves identically

00:10:57.030 --> 00:10:58.840
with the ROE in the business.

00:10:58.840 --> 00:11:02.430
And on a constant valuation,
absent any distributions,

00:11:02.430 --> 00:11:04.680
that's sort of my
very modest level

00:11:04.680 --> 00:11:06.590
of a proof of this notion.

00:11:06.590 --> 00:11:09.660
And it's a valuable
notion that's served us

00:11:09.660 --> 00:11:11.460
well for a long period of time.

00:11:11.460 --> 00:11:14.170
So then my next
question is, well,

00:11:14.170 --> 00:11:19.170
how is it that we identify an
investment which will likely

00:11:19.170 --> 00:11:21.980
lead us to an above-average
rate of return?

00:11:21.980 --> 00:11:28.080
What are the characteristics,
and what kinds of businesses

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:30.160
earn above average
rates of return?

00:11:30.160 --> 00:11:37.410
So we say very carefully that
we like to fish in the pond

00:11:37.410 --> 00:11:38.910
of high return businesses.

00:11:38.910 --> 00:11:42.240
And so it makes it much
easier for us to get our focus

00:11:42.240 --> 00:11:45.180
upfront, as we start
with the notion of,

00:11:45.180 --> 00:11:49.500
what kind of returns on capital
does that business earn?

00:11:49.500 --> 00:11:52.530
And just do something a little
bit interactive here today.

00:11:52.530 --> 00:11:59.280
If I asked Saurabh what
is the typical net margin

00:11:59.280 --> 00:12:03.060
of an American business
today in percentage terms,

00:12:03.060 --> 00:12:03.852
what would you say?

00:12:03.852 --> 00:12:04.934
SAURABH MADAAN: 10% to 15%

00:12:04.934 --> 00:12:06.600
CHUCK AKRE: So you
think it's 10, maybe

00:12:06.600 --> 00:12:08.310
a little bit above that.

00:12:08.310 --> 00:12:10.440
I'd suggest that
most people answer

00:12:10.440 --> 00:12:14.970
that it's probably in mid or
upper single digits, all right?

00:12:14.970 --> 00:12:16.950
And an investment that we own--

00:12:16.950 --> 00:12:18.600
I'll come back
around to later on--

00:12:18.600 --> 00:12:21.630
is MasterCard and Visa.

00:12:21.630 --> 00:12:23.850
And does anybody
want to guess what

00:12:23.850 --> 00:12:26.350
the net margins of
MasterCard, Visa are?

00:12:26.350 --> 00:12:27.090
AUDIENCE: 30, 40.

00:12:27.090 --> 00:12:27.500
CHUCK AKRE: There you go.

00:12:27.500 --> 00:12:29.370
So they're in the
mid-30s, you know?

00:12:29.370 --> 00:12:32.820
And you could cut
that in half twice,

00:12:32.820 --> 00:12:35.070
and at worst, it would
be an average business.

00:12:35.070 --> 00:12:37.800
It's extraordinary.

00:12:37.800 --> 00:12:39.810
And I actually was
talking to some people

00:12:39.810 --> 00:12:43.290
about this at the Munger
meeting the other day,

00:12:43.290 --> 00:12:46.770
people who are well-schooled in
the market, and good investors,

00:12:46.770 --> 00:12:48.750
and they had no idea.

00:12:48.750 --> 00:12:51.820
They just didn't
think of it that way.

00:12:51.820 --> 00:12:55.080
But that happens to be the way
we think about it, because we

00:12:55.080 --> 00:13:00.662
have this little idea that are
our returns will be affected

00:13:00.662 --> 00:13:03.120
by the quality of the business
and the rate at which it can

00:13:03.120 --> 00:13:06.660
grow the economic
value per share.

00:13:06.660 --> 00:13:08.460
And so, by the way,
and MasterCard,

00:13:08.460 --> 00:13:10.350
I can come back
to it, but it also

00:13:10.350 --> 00:13:14.410
then causes us to spend a lot
of time trying to figure out,

00:13:14.410 --> 00:13:16.530
well, why is that so?

00:13:16.530 --> 00:13:19.560
What is it about the essence
of that business that

00:13:19.560 --> 00:13:23.070
allows them to earn returns
that caused them to have

00:13:23.070 --> 00:13:25.740
a big bullseye on their
back, that everybody, all

00:13:25.740 --> 00:13:28.170
other companies want a
piece of a business that

00:13:28.170 --> 00:13:30.042
has returns that are that high?

00:13:32.820 --> 00:13:37.110
So in my office, for some
really unknown reason,

00:13:37.110 --> 00:13:41.700
I had on the desk an old
fashioned milking stool.

00:13:41.700 --> 00:13:43.680
And it had come to
me through my father,

00:13:43.680 --> 00:13:48.100
and it had come to him through
a business partner of his.

00:13:48.100 --> 00:13:52.980
And on the top of this platform,
it stands about that high,

00:13:52.980 --> 00:13:54.880
and it has three legs.

00:13:54.880 --> 00:13:56.921
And the first two
are in the front,

00:13:56.921 --> 00:13:58.920
and the third one is in
the middle, in the back,

00:13:58.920 --> 00:14:00.770
and they're splayed.

00:14:00.770 --> 00:14:04.470
And a farmer who was milking
his cow would grab that back leg

00:14:04.470 --> 00:14:06.390
and sort of just stick
it up under his behind

00:14:06.390 --> 00:14:08.190
as he sat down to milk a cow.

00:14:08.190 --> 00:14:11.110
This was in the old days
when they did it by hand.

00:14:11.110 --> 00:14:14.850
And so I was looking at that one
day, and I thought, you know,

00:14:14.850 --> 00:14:17.400
that's actually a
perfect construct

00:14:17.400 --> 00:14:20.280
for our notion about what
makes a valuable investment.

00:14:20.280 --> 00:14:22.120
We call it the
three-legged stool.

00:14:22.120 --> 00:14:24.020
So if you looked
at our material,

00:14:24.020 --> 00:14:27.780
our material is resplendent
with these three-legged stools.

00:14:27.780 --> 00:14:29.940
And the first leg of that--

00:14:29.940 --> 00:14:32.010
and we just use this
as a shorthand version,

00:14:32.010 --> 00:14:36.060
a construct to help us
think in very simple terms

00:14:36.060 --> 00:14:38.340
about, well, how do you find
these great investments?

00:14:38.340 --> 00:14:42.360
So the first leg is this issue
of a high return business,

00:14:42.360 --> 00:14:44.670
an exceptional business.

00:14:44.670 --> 00:14:46.600
MasterCard is an
exceptional business.

00:14:46.600 --> 00:14:50.700
The average business earns, call
it 8% after tax on earnings,

00:14:50.700 --> 00:14:52.710
and MasterCard earns 34%.

00:14:52.710 --> 00:14:54.390
That's exceptional.

00:14:54.390 --> 00:14:58.900
I mean, even if the average were
10%, 10% would be exception.

00:14:58.900 --> 00:15:01.140
But I mean, MasterCard's 34%.

00:15:01.140 --> 00:15:03.040
My god, that's
really incredible.

00:15:03.040 --> 00:15:06.240
So the first leg of the
stool that we talk about

00:15:06.240 --> 00:15:08.250
is the quality of the
business enterprise.

00:15:08.250 --> 00:15:11.680
And we spend a lot
of time going down

00:15:11.680 --> 00:15:14.710
this road that we call, what's
the essence of this business?

00:15:14.710 --> 00:15:16.510
What is it about
the business that's

00:15:16.510 --> 00:15:21.290
causing this unbelievable
rates of return to occur?

00:15:21.290 --> 00:15:25.480
The second leg of the stool,
then, goes into the operations.

00:15:25.480 --> 00:15:29.980
It has to do with the
people who run the business.

00:15:29.980 --> 00:15:33.550
And the shorthand
version of that

00:15:33.550 --> 00:15:36.130
is, we want them to have
both skill and integrity.

00:15:36.130 --> 00:15:38.500
But what we say is
that they've got

00:15:38.500 --> 00:15:42.400
a demonstrated record of being
just killers at operating

00:15:42.400 --> 00:15:43.330
their business.

00:15:43.330 --> 00:15:47.230
But in addition to that,
they treat us as partners

00:15:47.230 --> 00:15:48.965
even though they don't know us.

00:15:48.965 --> 00:15:50.770
And it's a really
important idea,

00:15:50.770 --> 00:15:54.190
because the reverse
of that is somebody

00:15:54.190 --> 00:15:57.880
I heard describe the other day,
is talking like Warren Buffett

00:15:57.880 --> 00:16:01.150
and acting like Ronald Perlman.

00:16:01.150 --> 00:16:04.480
And there are people out
there, and you'll find them,

00:16:04.480 --> 00:16:06.850
you'll run across
them, who do whatever

00:16:06.850 --> 00:16:09.760
they can to make sure that
public shareholders don't

00:16:09.760 --> 00:16:11.020
get their fair share.

00:16:11.020 --> 00:16:12.020
And we don't want that.

00:16:12.020 --> 00:16:15.040
We want, the same thing
happens at the company level

00:16:15.040 --> 00:16:16.790
to happen at the
per-share level.

00:16:16.790 --> 00:16:19.231
And these are
wonderfully-skilled operators

00:16:19.231 --> 00:16:19.730
as well.

00:16:19.730 --> 00:16:22.520
So first leg is the
quality of the business.

00:16:22.520 --> 00:16:24.020
The second leg is
really the quality

00:16:24.020 --> 00:16:25.730
of the people who
run the business.

00:16:25.730 --> 00:16:28.390
And then the third
leg is the issue

00:16:28.390 --> 00:16:30.430
that really helps
create the value,

00:16:30.430 --> 00:16:32.050
and that's the reinvestment.

00:16:32.050 --> 00:16:36.880
And there's a book out,
pretty current now,

00:16:36.880 --> 00:16:42.160
called "Dear Chairman," and it's
about activists, and companies,

00:16:42.160 --> 00:16:46.120
and trying to change the
behavior of companies,

00:16:46.120 --> 00:16:49.380
typically, because of their
reinvestment histories.

00:16:49.380 --> 00:16:54.100
And if a business has a great
high return on the owner's

00:16:54.100 --> 00:16:57.040
capital, we would
love for them to be

00:16:57.040 --> 00:17:00.250
able to take all the free cash
they generate and put it back

00:17:00.250 --> 00:17:01.870
into that business
to continue to earn

00:17:01.870 --> 00:17:03.760
those high rates of return.

00:17:03.760 --> 00:17:07.240
It's way more efficient than
paying us a dividend and all

00:17:07.240 --> 00:17:10.869
of those things, and that's what
creates the compounding effect.

00:17:10.869 --> 00:17:16.180
And when I get around to
compounding, you know,

00:17:16.180 --> 00:17:19.329
I always use the example--
you all have seen it

00:17:19.329 --> 00:17:20.800
on the web-- about the penny.

00:17:20.800 --> 00:17:24.130
And so I'm going to ask
this engineer right here,

00:17:24.130 --> 00:17:30.250
would you rather have, in this
hand, $750,000, or a penny

00:17:30.250 --> 00:17:33.032
doubled every day for 30 days.

00:17:33.032 --> 00:17:34.240
So you want the penny, right?

00:17:34.240 --> 00:17:35.150
I knew that.

00:17:35.150 --> 00:17:39.626
So instead of $750,000, I'm
going to make it $2 million

00:17:39.626 --> 00:17:42.880
in my right hand, versus
the penny, doubled

00:17:42.880 --> 00:17:43.840
every day for 30 days.

00:17:46.560 --> 00:17:47.670
You still want the penny?

00:17:47.670 --> 00:17:48.560
So I figured that.

00:17:48.560 --> 00:17:51.596
How about $2 million and one?

00:17:51.596 --> 00:17:54.549
Well, I mean, this choice,
it was $2 million before,

00:17:54.549 --> 00:17:55.590
you still took the penny.

00:17:55.590 --> 00:17:59.030
I'm saying, how about if I
make it $2 million and one?

00:17:59.030 --> 00:18:00.238
AUDIENCE: That's a lot money.

00:18:00.238 --> 00:18:01.238
I'd pick the $2 million.

00:18:01.238 --> 00:18:02.410
CHUCK AKRE: Yeah, see?

00:18:02.410 --> 00:18:04.890
Now, who knows, right
off the top of the head,

00:18:04.890 --> 00:18:06.716
what that figure is?

00:18:06.716 --> 00:18:07.715
AUDIENCE: $10.8 million?

00:18:07.715 --> 00:18:09.650
CHUCK AKRE: Yeah,
it's $10.8 million.

00:18:09.650 --> 00:18:14.700
It's $10,737,000 or something
like that and some change.

00:18:14.700 --> 00:18:18.690
And so the simple arithmetic
is, it's 100% return for 30

00:18:18.690 --> 00:18:20.940
periods, you know?

00:18:20.940 --> 00:18:23.610
And that's the power
of compounding.

00:18:23.610 --> 00:18:27.180
And so the really great
thing about compounding,

00:18:27.180 --> 00:18:30.870
I tell people is, if you have a
stock that's gone up 10 times,

00:18:30.870 --> 00:18:33.090
the next time it
doubles, it's gone up 20,

00:18:33.090 --> 00:18:35.850
and the next time it doubles,
it's going up 40 times.

00:18:35.850 --> 00:18:36.720
What?

00:18:36.720 --> 00:18:41.570
You know compound interest
and compound return is just--

00:18:41.570 --> 00:18:43.396
it's staggering.

00:18:43.396 --> 00:18:45.270
Actually, I have a
correspondence with Warren

00:18:45.270 --> 00:18:49.290
Buffett about this,
and he always has said,

00:18:49.290 --> 00:18:53.320
as it relates to compounding,
either you get it or you don't.

00:18:53.320 --> 00:18:54.930
And I wrote him a
letter and I said,

00:18:54.930 --> 00:18:56.370
that was not my experience.

00:18:56.370 --> 00:19:01.380
My experience was, I didn't
get it until I experienced it.

00:19:01.380 --> 00:19:03.570
And that goes to this
whole issue of investing.

00:19:03.570 --> 00:19:07.290
I have never been able to learn
from other people's mistakes,

00:19:07.290 --> 00:19:07.920
you know?

00:19:07.920 --> 00:19:09.473
I have to make my own.

00:19:09.473 --> 00:19:10.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:10.240 --> 00:19:17.220
And so this process is
designed to help me,

00:19:17.220 --> 00:19:21.120
and my colleagues, and
partners have focus,

00:19:21.120 --> 00:19:24.920
as it relates to how
we're going to invest.

00:19:24.920 --> 00:19:27.080
Contrary to that
is everything you

00:19:27.080 --> 00:19:31.760
see on the TV in the morning, on
Squawk Box or all those things.

00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:34.310
And they have a
different business model.

00:19:34.310 --> 00:19:37.160
And their business
model is mostly

00:19:37.160 --> 00:19:41.570
supported by financial
institutions and other consumer

00:19:41.570 --> 00:19:44.360
institutions who
want your eyeballs.

00:19:44.360 --> 00:19:47.360
And if it's a brokerage
firm that's sponsoring it,

00:19:47.360 --> 00:19:50.630
the definition of a broker is
to create transactions, right?

00:19:50.630 --> 00:19:52.340
Your advertising
people, they want

00:19:52.340 --> 00:19:55.260
to create transactions, right?

00:19:55.260 --> 00:19:57.590
And what's the best way
to create a transaction

00:19:57.590 --> 00:19:58.970
in the brokerage industry?

00:19:58.970 --> 00:20:01.790
Create what I call
false expectations.

00:20:01.790 --> 00:20:05.658
And the false expectations
are the notion

00:20:05.658 --> 00:20:10.210
that XYZ Company earns
$1.37 in the quarter.

00:20:10.210 --> 00:20:12.220
And the first thing
that happens when

00:20:12.220 --> 00:20:15.310
they release their
quarterly reports is,

00:20:15.310 --> 00:20:18.160
everybody comes out and
says, oh, they earned $1 38.

00:20:18.160 --> 00:20:19.150
They beat by a penny.

00:20:19.150 --> 00:20:19.900
You better buy it.

00:20:19.900 --> 00:20:21.132
Or they earned $1.36.

00:20:21.132 --> 00:20:22.090
They missed by a penny.

00:20:22.090 --> 00:20:22.960
You better buy.

00:20:22.960 --> 00:20:25.240
Well, if you stop
and think about it,

00:20:25.240 --> 00:20:27.550
unless you're very
adept at trading

00:20:27.550 --> 00:20:31.980
the market on a daily basis,
it's a sure loser for you.

00:20:31.980 --> 00:20:34.290
It's bad for your
economic health.

00:20:34.290 --> 00:20:37.270
And as it relates to trading
the market on a daily basis,

00:20:37.270 --> 00:20:39.820
you know, there are very
powerful computer algorithms

00:20:39.820 --> 00:20:43.150
out there using all
kinds of information

00:20:43.150 --> 00:20:46.400
not available to most of us
that are competing against you.

00:20:46.400 --> 00:20:48.740
So I just make that observation.

00:20:48.740 --> 00:20:55.510
We try very hard to be investors
in the value of businesses,

00:20:55.510 --> 00:20:58.030
as opposed to speculators
in the price of shares.

00:21:01.420 --> 00:21:04.590
So now do you remember
what a penny doubled

00:21:04.590 --> 00:21:05.958
every day for 30 years is?

00:21:05.958 --> 00:21:06.894
[LAUGHS]

00:21:06.894 --> 00:21:08.770
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:08.770 --> 00:21:10.195
Don't lose sight of that.

00:21:10.195 --> 00:21:17.530
[LAUGHS] So we tell our clients
and our prospective clients

00:21:17.530 --> 00:21:21.850
that our goal is to
compound their capital

00:21:21.850 --> 00:21:25.300
at an above average
rate, while incurring

00:21:25.300 --> 00:21:27.492
a below average level of risk.

00:21:27.492 --> 00:21:29.200
So let's start with
the back end of that.

00:21:29.200 --> 00:21:32.540
What do we mean by a below
average level of risk?

00:21:32.540 --> 00:21:35.950
Well, the businesses
we own typically

00:21:35.950 --> 00:21:38.660
have the following
characteristics.

00:21:38.660 --> 00:21:40.900
They have more growth.

00:21:40.900 --> 00:21:44.300
They have higher
returns on capital.

00:21:44.300 --> 00:21:48.200
They have stronger balance
sheets, and frequently,

00:21:48.200 --> 00:21:50.870
lower valuations
than the market.

00:21:50.870 --> 00:21:54.230
So on their face,
they are less risky.

00:21:54.230 --> 00:21:56.540
It's just, it's observable.

00:21:56.540 --> 00:21:59.480
It doesn't have anything
to do with volatility,

00:21:59.480 --> 00:22:02.300
because our belief
is, volatility is

00:22:02.300 --> 00:22:04.850
a risk only in the short run.

00:22:04.850 --> 00:22:09.020
If you have an obligation
in a year to buy a house

00:22:09.020 --> 00:22:11.720
or to do something
like that, you probably

00:22:11.720 --> 00:22:14.810
don't want to speculate
with that cash

00:22:14.810 --> 00:22:16.760
that you have set
aside for that.

00:22:16.760 --> 00:22:18.710
But if it's five
years or three years,

00:22:18.710 --> 00:22:21.020
you have the ability,
put that money

00:22:21.020 --> 00:22:22.610
to work and have
it work for you.

00:22:22.610 --> 00:22:26.570
So volatility is not in
our lexicon, basically,

00:22:26.570 --> 00:22:28.850
in terms of risk.

00:22:28.850 --> 00:22:30.830
And we've already talked
about what average is,

00:22:30.830 --> 00:22:34.070
and we think average is roughly
high single digits, maybe

00:22:34.070 --> 00:22:37.550
low double digits,
and it has to do

00:22:37.550 --> 00:22:40.730
with what the overall
interest rate environment is.

00:22:40.730 --> 00:22:43.850
And so there are lots of
investors, Michael Steinhardt

00:22:43.850 --> 00:22:47.020
and people like that,
who retired with records

00:22:47.020 --> 00:22:49.040
of very high rates of returns.

00:22:49.040 --> 00:22:50.630
But that was
against the backdrop

00:22:50.630 --> 00:22:54.980
that, in January of
1981, the long bond,

00:22:54.980 --> 00:22:58.100
the 30-year treasury
yielded 15 and 3/8%,

00:22:58.100 --> 00:23:00.470
and prime rate was 21 and 1/2%.

00:23:00.470 --> 00:23:02.720
So it was in a backdrop
in which rates were much

00:23:02.720 --> 00:23:04.570
higher than they are currently.

00:23:04.570 --> 00:23:08.360
So returns in all businesses
are lower these days,

00:23:08.360 --> 00:23:11.240
and my guess is, average
these days would probably

00:23:11.240 --> 00:23:16.780
be at the low end of that sort
of high single digits number.

00:23:16.780 --> 00:23:19.870
And because it's an average
we're talking about,

00:23:19.870 --> 00:23:22.910
it does not mean that we will
have a return in any given

00:23:22.910 --> 00:23:24.740
year that's better than that.

00:23:24.740 --> 00:23:28.490
It means, to us, over a
period of 5 years or 10 years,

00:23:28.490 --> 00:23:32.970
our returns are very likely
to be well above that number.

00:23:32.970 --> 00:23:36.700
But I would say, observably,
maybe a third of the years

00:23:36.700 --> 00:23:40.220
in the last 25 we maybe
have done less well in them

00:23:40.220 --> 00:23:44.450
than the S&amp;P, which, we use that
