00:28:26.130 --> 00:28:31.010
And as a builder and developer,
he borrowed a lot of money

00:28:31.010 --> 00:28:32.010
in his lifetime.

00:28:32.010 --> 00:28:35.630
And he told me that he had
been able to avoid ever having

00:28:35.630 --> 00:28:38.060
his wife sign-- co-sign a loan.

00:28:38.060 --> 00:28:42.380
That's a really important
measure of risk understanding.

00:28:42.380 --> 00:28:44.510
And so I got involved.

00:28:44.510 --> 00:28:46.640
And it was after
that, that he bought

00:28:46.640 --> 00:28:49.790
another racetrack in West
Virginia, and about an hour

00:28:49.790 --> 00:28:52.130
and a half from
Washington and Baltimore,

00:28:52.130 --> 00:28:54.050
and converted that
into a casino that

00:28:54.050 --> 00:28:57.410
now has 5,000 slot machines.

00:28:57.410 --> 00:29:02.060
And he went on become
the largest non-Las Vegas

00:29:02.060 --> 00:29:06.390
and non-Atlantic City casino
operator in the country.

00:29:06.390 --> 00:29:10.520
And it's another case where we
made 10 to 20 times our money

00:29:10.520 --> 00:29:11.750
in our accounts.

00:29:11.750 --> 00:29:16.790
Again, this was a situation
of high returns on capital,

00:29:16.790 --> 00:29:21.270
low valuation, major
shareholder owner and operator,

00:29:21.270 --> 00:29:22.460
and a low valuation.

00:29:22.460 --> 00:29:27.136
It was a huge opportunity
for growth, going forward.

00:29:27.136 --> 00:29:30.080
And then, in current times,
we talked a little bit

00:29:30.080 --> 00:29:33.500
about MasterCard.

00:29:33.500 --> 00:29:36.980
Some things that are
interesting about MasterCard,

00:29:36.980 --> 00:29:41.300
we purchased originally
in February of 2010.

00:29:41.300 --> 00:29:43.970
And this is when the
Dodd-Frank discussions

00:29:43.970 --> 00:29:46.790
were going on in Congress
after the financial crisis,

00:29:46.790 --> 00:29:49.460
and more particularly, about
the Durbin amendment, which

00:29:49.460 --> 00:29:53.210
had to do with domestic
debit transactions.

00:29:53.210 --> 00:29:56.930
The long and short of it is, we
bought the stock at an average

00:29:56.930 --> 00:30:01.700
price of $22.20 in
February of 2010.

00:30:01.700 --> 00:30:06.710
Today, it's $109,
something like that.

00:30:06.710 --> 00:30:10.610
So we've made five times our
money in six years, seven,

00:30:10.610 --> 00:30:12.020
you know, something like that.

00:30:12.020 --> 00:30:15.350
And the reason was that
here is a business that

00:30:15.350 --> 00:30:19.250
had fantastic returns, as
we've already talked about.

00:30:19.250 --> 00:30:20.210
It had a low valuation.

00:30:20.210 --> 00:30:24.140
The valuation in
February of 2010

00:30:24.140 --> 00:30:26.840
was something like
13 or 14 times.

00:30:26.840 --> 00:30:29.360
It was growing its free cash
flow per share at a rate

00:30:29.360 --> 00:30:30.890
much faster than that.

00:30:30.890 --> 00:30:33.200
And we had a good
thing happen with it,

00:30:33.200 --> 00:30:37.560
that we'd been to meet the
new CEO, Ajay Banga, who's

00:30:37.560 --> 00:30:43.540
a Punjabi, and a really bright,
