00:30:43.540 --> 00:30:46.240
And so, you and I
were talking earlier

00:30:46.240 --> 00:30:48.290
about the interaction of people.

00:30:48.290 --> 00:30:52.220
And so we see him in a
setting with other executives

00:30:52.220 --> 00:30:55.400
in his firm, and he's first
name basis, kidding with them.

00:30:55.400 --> 00:30:56.630
They kid with him.

00:30:56.630 --> 00:30:58.130
All of these things
are important.

00:30:58.130 --> 00:30:59.510
Just the things--
you know, I talked

00:30:59.510 --> 00:31:00.884
about reading
business biography,

00:31:00.884 --> 00:31:03.350
you get a feel for
how people behave,

00:31:03.350 --> 00:31:05.890
and how they deal with
their colleagues, and so on.

00:31:05.890 --> 00:31:08.240
And so we've made
five times our money

00:31:08.240 --> 00:31:10.910
in six short years in an
extraordinary business.

00:31:10.910 --> 00:31:13.430
Now, if you remember
what I talked about,

00:31:13.430 --> 00:31:17.420
the third leg,
reinvestment, their returns

00:31:17.420 --> 00:31:20.480
are so high that
they can't possibly

00:31:20.480 --> 00:31:24.170
find another place to reinvest
their money at that rate

00:31:24.170 --> 00:31:25.160
and get that return.

00:31:25.160 --> 00:31:30.590
So our compounding is diminished
modestly because of that.

00:31:30.590 --> 00:31:33.900
So they buy in scads of
stock, they pay a dividend,

00:31:33.900 --> 00:31:36.680
they invest a lot
in new technologies,

00:31:36.680 --> 00:31:41.934
all relating to what I call the
electronic exchange of value.

00:31:41.934 --> 00:31:43.850
I mean, that's really
the business they're in,

00:31:43.850 --> 00:31:47.750
and we don't know what form
factor it will take in years,

00:31:47.750 --> 00:31:50.480
but they're well-positioned
in all of the things that

00:31:50.480 --> 00:31:52.420
are going on today.

00:31:52.420 --> 00:31:55.610
Another company that
is relatively new to us

00:31:55.610 --> 00:31:59.600
is Moody's, and we bought
our Moody's originally

00:31:59.600 --> 00:32:01.760
in January of 2012.

00:32:01.760 --> 00:32:07.340
And we paid about $39, a
little less than $39 for it.

00:32:07.340 --> 00:32:09.650
Today, it's $110.

00:32:09.650 --> 00:32:14.150
And so we have a case
where we've made 2 and 1/2,

00:32:14.150 --> 00:32:15.890
2 and 3/4 times our money.

00:32:15.890 --> 00:32:20.310
Again, the same idea,
a great business.

00:32:20.310 --> 00:32:25.940
After Dodd-Frank, the government
authorized another six or eight

00:32:25.940 --> 00:32:28.370
rating agencies to exist.

00:32:28.370 --> 00:32:31.040
I'm sure there's not a person
in this room who can tell you

00:32:31.040 --> 00:32:32.360
the name of any of them.

00:32:32.360 --> 00:32:33.830
It's a market-driven thing.

00:32:33.830 --> 00:32:36.380
It's not regulatory-driven.

00:32:36.380 --> 00:32:39.110
And so any company
that issues debt

00:32:39.110 --> 00:32:40.850
has to go out and
get a rating on it.

00:32:40.850 --> 00:32:43.550
And there are really
three rating agencies--

00:32:43.550 --> 00:32:45.860
Moody's, S&amp;P, and Fitch.

00:32:45.860 --> 00:32:49.550
The market is divided,
like, 40%, 40%, and 20%.

00:32:49.550 --> 00:32:52.460
Fitch has had 20%
for nearly 100 years.

00:32:52.460 --> 00:32:54.880
They just can't seem to grow
it any larger than that,

00:32:54.880 --> 00:32:56.450
and it's market-driven.

00:32:56.450 --> 00:32:59.210
And if you sit on the
board of a company that's

00:32:59.210 --> 00:33:01.970
about to raise
debt, and you go out

00:33:01.970 --> 00:33:04.460
and you don't get a
rating on your debt,

00:33:04.460 --> 00:33:08.320
and you have a bad effect in the
market, you have a liability.

00:33:08.320 --> 00:33:13.430
So it's a fascinating business
that, again, market forces

00:33:13.430 --> 00:33:17.000
allow it to have very high
returns on its capital.

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:21.520
Another company that we've
been involved with for,

00:33:21.520 --> 00:33:26.390
gee, almost 10 years is
a company called Enstar.

00:33:26.390 --> 00:33:30.260
And I sat on their
board for five years

00:33:30.260 --> 00:33:32.210
because I wanted to
try to understand

00:33:32.210 --> 00:33:33.660
how the business
really operated,

00:33:33.660 --> 00:33:36.050
and it's a complicated business.

00:33:36.050 --> 00:33:39.980
They buy insurance
which is in runoff.

00:33:39.980 --> 00:33:43.820
And that is, operating insurance
companies periodically decide,

00:33:43.820 --> 00:33:45.860
well, we don't want to
be in homeowners anymore,

00:33:45.860 --> 00:33:48.500
or we don't want to be
in long haul trucking

00:33:48.500 --> 00:33:51.350
anymore, or whatever, and
they run that business off.

00:33:51.350 --> 00:33:53.360
And they're required
to keep assets

00:33:53.360 --> 00:33:56.120
to support those liabilities
by the regulators

00:33:56.120 --> 00:33:59.020
until that business is gone.

00:33:59.020 --> 00:34:03.020
And executives in
businesses like insurance

00:34:03.020 --> 00:34:06.380
who have aspirations
in their career

00:34:06.380 --> 00:34:08.290
would not like to be
placed in the runoff.

00:34:08.290 --> 00:34:11.250
It's sort of the back
room of the business.

00:34:11.250 --> 00:34:14.310
And this group of people
who started this company

00:34:14.310 --> 00:34:18.980
are chartered
accountants by training.

00:34:18.980 --> 00:34:23.270
And they're headquartered
in South Africa, and Dublin,

00:34:23.270 --> 00:34:25.070
and Bermuda, and London.

00:34:25.070 --> 00:34:26.719
And they travel
all over the world

00:34:26.719 --> 00:34:28.969
all the time, in
search of trying

00:34:28.969 --> 00:34:31.310
to find these little
pieces of business.

00:34:31.310 --> 00:34:33.830
I've seen instances where they
worked on a piece of business

00:34:33.830 --> 00:34:35.239
for five or six years.

00:34:35.239 --> 00:34:38.389
They're very patient,
very disciplined.

00:34:38.389 --> 00:34:43.580
And when I got involved
in this company in 2007,

00:34:43.580 --> 00:34:45.230
it had had a record
of compounding book

00:34:45.230 --> 00:34:48.500
value per share a
little bit north of 20%.

00:34:48.500 --> 00:34:51.469
But it was also
three times book.

00:34:51.469 --> 00:34:59.810
And I paid $102.90 for
my first shares in 2007.

00:34:59.810 --> 00:35:02.170
And today, it's
worth about $195.

00:35:02.170 --> 00:35:03.860
So it's not been a
very good investment.

00:35:03.860 --> 00:35:07.770
And you know, I mean, I've
essentially doubled my money,

00:35:07.770 --> 00:35:09.050
but it's taken 10 years.

00:35:09.050 --> 00:35:13.940
So that number, obviously,
roughly around 7%, compounded.

00:35:13.940 --> 00:35:18.230
But then the valuation got
more attractive periodically,

00:35:18.230 --> 00:35:22.940
and in 2009, I was able
to buy some stock at $56.

00:35:22.940 --> 00:35:25.740
So my return there
is nearly four times

00:35:25.740 --> 00:35:26.800
and that sort of stuff.

00:35:26.800 --> 00:35:29.440
And so, that goes back to this
issue I was talking about,

00:35:29.440 --> 00:35:31.990
your starting valuation.

00:35:31.990 --> 00:35:35.870
And you know, when I paid three
times book for this company

00:35:35.870 --> 00:35:40.290
in '07 and it had a history
of compounding book at 20%,

00:35:40.290 --> 00:35:43.280
had it been able to
continue to compound at 20%,

00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:44.600
I would have done much better.

00:35:44.600 --> 00:35:46.640
But their rate of
return has come down,

00:35:46.640 --> 00:35:48.800
just like it has
in all businesses,

00:35:48.800 --> 00:35:52.520
as we've had this secular
decline in interest rates

00:35:52.520 --> 00:35:54.770
for 36 years as a backdrop.

00:35:54.770 --> 00:35:58.610
Everybody's business returns
are lower, nearly everybody.

00:35:58.610 --> 00:36:04.580
And so those are sort of
five examples of businesses

00:36:04.580 --> 00:36:06.890
that we own or have
owned, where we've

00:36:06.890 --> 00:36:11.330
had these great returns as a
result of using this process,

00:36:11.330 --> 00:36:15.140
using our process, we call
it the three-legged stool,

00:36:15.140 --> 00:36:17.690
of identifying
businesses that we

00:36:17.690 --> 00:36:23.360
think are likely to give us a
return that's above average.

00:36:23.360 --> 00:36:24.830
I'm getting near the end here.

00:36:24.830 --> 00:36:26.550
You're getting anxious.

00:36:26.550 --> 00:36:27.140
I know that.

00:36:27.140 --> 00:36:29.600
So I'll give you a few
quotes out of Einstein,

00:36:29.600 --> 00:36:32.780
because I find him
simply a great thinker.

00:36:32.780 --> 00:36:34.400
You should make
everything as simple

00:36:34.400 --> 00:36:37.700
as possible, but no simpler.

00:36:37.700 --> 00:36:39.800
You'll have to think
about it a minute.

00:36:39.800 --> 00:36:42.800
The difference between
stupidity and genius

00:36:42.800 --> 00:36:45.728
is that genius has
its limits, you know?

00:36:45.728 --> 00:36:48.170
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:48.170 --> 00:36:52.400
We cannot solve our problems
with the same thinking that we

00:36:52.400 --> 00:36:56.240
used to create them, huh?

00:36:56.240 --> 00:37:01.700
The only source of
knowledge is experience.

00:37:01.700 --> 00:37:04.460
Imagination is more
important than knowledge.

00:37:04.460 --> 00:37:06.110
I told Saurabh that's
what it actually

00:37:06.110 --> 00:37:09.290
says on the front of my book.

00:37:09.290 --> 00:37:12.950
And the true test
of intelligence

00:37:12.950 --> 00:37:16.860
is not knowledge,
but imagination.

00:37:16.860 --> 00:37:19.195
So we put our own little
quote on the end of that.

00:37:19.195 --> 00:37:22.800
It's an old saw which says
that good judgment comes

00:37:22.800 --> 00:37:25.667
from experience, and experience
comes from bad judgment.

00:37:25.667 --> 00:37:31.980
[CHUCKLES] So in conclusion, we
work in a town with one traffic

00:37:31.980 --> 00:37:33.090
light.

00:37:33.090 --> 00:37:37.440
And I say it makes the decision
process so much simpler.

00:37:37.440 --> 00:37:39.840
Einstein, make things
as simple as possible.

00:37:39.840 --> 00:37:42.090
We tell people when they
get to the light, turn.

00:37:42.090 --> 00:37:45.990
Sooner or later, they'll
get to us in town.

00:37:45.990 --> 00:37:49.950
And what's really important is
that, in a campus like this,

00:37:49.950 --> 00:37:54.360
or in Central Park South in
New York, or in downtown San

00:37:54.360 --> 00:37:57.450
Francisco, or Los Angeles,
we'd be surrounded

00:37:57.450 --> 00:38:02.570
by hundreds of people who
are very bright and very

00:38:02.570 --> 00:38:03.981
interesting.

00:38:03.981 --> 00:38:06.230
And the reason we're in a
town with one traffic light,

00:38:06.230 --> 00:38:10.490
away from that, is that their
stuff would be intellectually

00:38:10.490 --> 00:38:13.400
appealing to us and
it would distract us

00:38:13.400 --> 00:38:15.849
from what it is we do well.

00:38:15.849 --> 00:38:17.390
And that's a really
important notion.

00:38:17.390 --> 00:38:19.700
Warren talked about
getting out of New York

00:38:19.700 --> 00:38:22.250
and going back to Omaha
when he was a young man.

00:38:22.250 --> 00:38:23.830
It's the same idea.

00:38:23.830 --> 00:38:27.530
And not that being in
your midst wouldn't

00:38:27.530 --> 00:38:30.830
be unbelievably fulfilling,
or being in New York,

00:38:30.830 --> 00:38:31.840
or something like that.

00:38:31.840 --> 00:38:35.330
It's that It distracts
us from what we do well.

00:38:35.330 --> 00:38:37.220
And so, that's a
really important thing,

00:38:37.220 --> 00:38:39.890
is you're thinking about
being an investor is

00:38:39.890 --> 00:38:42.380
to create the situation
for yourself, that you have

00:38:42.380 --> 00:38:47.210
the ability to apply what it is
that you've learned and found

00:38:47.210 --> 00:38:50.750
valuable in investing, as
opposed to listening what

00:38:50.750 --> 00:38:53.240
Squawk Box, or your next door
neighbor, or your suite mate

00:38:53.240 --> 00:38:54.340
says, something like that.

00:38:57.810 --> 00:39:00.420
Make things as simple as
possible, but no simpler.

00:39:00.420 --> 00:39:03.900
Imagination is more important
than knowledge, you know?

00:39:03.900 --> 00:39:07.350
So I say, simply use
your own observations.

00:39:07.350 --> 00:39:08.940
It's very important.

00:39:08.940 --> 00:39:13.260
Peter Lynch used to talk about
buying the things that you

00:39:13.260 --> 00:39:14.889
see happening.

00:39:14.889 --> 00:39:16.680
In the shopping center,
there's a new store

00:39:16.680 --> 00:39:21.210
and they're getting a lot
of traffic, or whatever.

00:39:21.210 --> 00:39:24.180
Do you all know
who Peter Lynch is?

00:39:24.180 --> 00:39:26.340
I mean, he had a
really unusual talent.

00:39:26.340 --> 00:39:29.380
He had 1,200 securities in
the Fidelity Magellan Fund.

00:39:29.380 --> 00:39:31.320
He ran it for eight
or nine years,

00:39:31.320 --> 00:39:33.630
and had a phenomenal
record and so on.

00:39:33.630 --> 00:39:36.600
But he had 1,200 securities.

00:39:36.600 --> 00:39:37.470
I mean, imagine.

00:39:37.470 --> 00:39:39.172
So I was in, seeing him one day.

00:39:39.172 --> 00:39:41.630
And what he would do-- we were
talking about this earlier--

00:39:41.630 --> 00:39:44.640
is if he found an
industry that he liked,

00:39:44.640 --> 00:39:47.187
he would buy every
company in that industry,

00:39:47.187 --> 00:39:48.270
put them in his portfolio.

00:39:48.270 --> 00:39:50.280
And then he'd eliminate
them one at a time,

00:39:50.280 --> 00:39:54.180
as he kept honing in on who
were the best ones and so on.

00:39:54.180 --> 00:39:55.550
It's not a talent that I have.

00:39:58.890 --> 00:40:00.450
And then I say, just
because you have

00:40:00.450 --> 00:40:03.910
a big brain doesn't mean you
could be good at investing.

00:40:03.910 --> 00:40:05.490
And that's an
important thing, too.

00:40:05.490 --> 00:40:07.650
And finally, there
is no correct answer.

00:40:07.650 --> 00:40:08.670
There is no correct way.

00:40:08.670 --> 00:40:11.010
This is just the
way it works for us.

