00:40:38.604 --> 00:40:39.270
CHUCK AKRE: Yes.

00:40:39.270 --> 00:40:41.610
SAURABH MADAAN: And you were
talking about your kids.

00:40:41.610 --> 00:40:43.740
And if I remember
correctly, none of them

00:40:43.740 --> 00:40:45.430
are doing what you
did in your career.

00:40:45.430 --> 00:40:46.350
CHUCK AKRE: Correct.

00:40:46.350 --> 00:40:48.690
SAURABH MADAAN: And I
mean, over the years

00:40:48.690 --> 00:40:52.050
of successful investing,
by the numbers that you've

00:40:52.050 --> 00:40:55.080
shared with us, I'm sure you've
made a little bit of money

00:40:55.080 --> 00:40:57.120
for yourself.

00:40:57.120 --> 00:41:00.170
CHUCK AKRE: I'm not
worried about my next meal.

00:41:00.170 --> 00:41:01.920
SAURABH MADAAN: Yeah,
that's what I meant.

00:41:01.920 --> 00:41:04.170
I was just curious,
what are your thoughts?

00:41:04.170 --> 00:41:08.730
You said that you believe it is
important to let your kids have

00:41:08.730 --> 00:41:10.110
their own struggles in life.

00:41:10.110 --> 00:41:13.050
So talk to us a little bit about
family, about raising kids,

00:41:13.050 --> 00:41:15.460
about giving money away, maybe.

00:41:15.460 --> 00:41:19.620
CHUCK AKRE: So my
wife and I spend

00:41:19.620 --> 00:41:21.450
a reasonable amount
of time figuring out

00:41:21.450 --> 00:41:27.065
how we can put the money
to use in places that

00:41:27.065 --> 00:41:29.760
will be advantaged by it,
as it relates to the things

00:41:29.760 --> 00:41:34.110
that we're interested in, or
land conservation, health care

00:41:34.110 --> 00:41:38.600
issues, education, shelter,
things of that nature.

00:41:38.600 --> 00:41:41.770
And so we pursue
that significantly,

00:41:41.770 --> 00:41:44.830
as so many people do.

00:41:44.830 --> 00:41:48.360
And then it creates an
issue within the family,

00:41:48.360 --> 00:41:51.930
where we've developed an asset
base that we certainly never

00:41:51.930 --> 00:41:54.630
expected to have.

00:41:54.630 --> 00:41:59.340
And we've seen, particularly
where we live and work,

00:41:59.340 --> 00:42:00.340
in Middleburg Virginia--

00:42:00.340 --> 00:42:01.960
You know, Paul
Mellon lived there,

00:42:01.960 --> 00:42:04.140
and Jackie Mars lives
there, and there's

00:42:04.140 --> 00:42:05.850
a lot of wealth in that area.

00:42:05.850 --> 00:42:08.670
And we've had a
chance to see people

00:42:08.670 --> 00:42:13.230
who have been, well, as we would
say, they're on scholarship,

00:42:13.230 --> 00:42:15.760
or they're on full scholarship.

00:42:15.760 --> 00:42:19.260
And we see some of those
whose lives are really

00:42:19.260 --> 00:42:22.440
up-ended because of the fact
that they have a vast amount

00:42:22.440 --> 00:42:24.790
of capital available to them.

00:42:24.790 --> 00:42:27.570
They don't have to
work, and they don't.

00:42:27.570 --> 00:42:30.930
And so, the phrase
that my wife and I use

00:42:30.930 --> 00:42:34.080
is, we don't want to deprive
our children of the opportunity

00:42:34.080 --> 00:42:35.020
to struggle.

00:42:35.020 --> 00:42:37.980
Struggle in my own life
has been very valuable.

00:42:37.980 --> 00:42:39.750
I was telling Daniel
yesterday, there

00:42:39.750 --> 00:42:41.400
have been a number
of times in my life,

00:42:41.400 --> 00:42:45.450
that if your glasses had the
right rose color in them,

00:42:45.450 --> 00:42:48.430
my assets would
equal my liabilities.

00:42:48.430 --> 00:42:51.220
But you had to have the right
color rose glasses, you know?

00:42:51.220 --> 00:42:55.630
And so those experiences
have been valuable to me

00:42:55.630 --> 00:42:58.677
as a human being, and as
an investor, and so on.

00:42:58.677 --> 00:43:01.260
And so, that's one of the things
that we think about, and talk

00:43:01.260 --> 00:43:03.027
about, and work out.

00:43:03.027 --> 00:43:04.110
SAURABH MADAAN: Thank you.

00:43:04.110 --> 00:43:05.460
That was great.

00:43:05.460 --> 00:43:07.662
You also mentioned that
you are a voracious reader.

00:43:07.662 --> 00:43:08.370
CHUCK AKRE: Yeah.

00:43:08.370 --> 00:43:09.870
SAURABH MADAAN: So
can you mention--

00:43:09.870 --> 00:43:11.784
CHUCK AKRE: And a
slow reader, too.

00:43:11.784 --> 00:43:14.200
SAURABH MADAAN: And they say
that slow reading is actually

00:43:14.200 --> 00:43:15.030
real reading, but--

00:43:15.030 --> 00:43:19.890
[LAUGHS] So I was curious.

00:43:19.890 --> 00:43:23.070
Name a few books, if
you can, that you think

00:43:23.070 --> 00:43:25.650
are maybe under-appreciated,
or a little bit

00:43:25.650 --> 00:43:29.490
under the radar, or
people would learn things

00:43:29.490 --> 00:43:31.590
from reading about them.

00:43:31.590 --> 00:43:34.890
CHUCK AKRE: Well, you know, I
mentioned that pretty new book

00:43:34.890 --> 00:43:36.635
out called "Dear Chairman."

00:43:36.635 --> 00:43:44.060
And actually, it's a lesson
in behavior of human beings.

00:43:44.060 --> 00:43:48.660
It's a lesson in thinking
about making judgments about

00:43:48.660 --> 00:43:51.210
whether or not
business executives use

00:43:51.210 --> 00:43:56.154
their assets well, in terms
of compounding their capital.

00:43:56.154 --> 00:43:58.320
I mentioned the book, "100
to 1 in the Market," that

00:43:58.320 --> 00:43:59.790
came out in '72.

00:43:59.790 --> 00:44:02.070
I've talked about that
a lot, and so people are

00:44:02.070 --> 00:44:03.900
reasonably familiar with it.

00:44:03.900 --> 00:44:06.930
But a few years ago,
they'd never heard of it.

00:44:06.930 --> 00:44:11.117
And the big idea in that is
the issue of compounding.

00:44:11.117 --> 00:44:13.200
Even though he doesn't
talk about that explicitly,

00:44:13.200 --> 00:44:15.240
he lists all kinds
of characteristics

00:44:15.240 --> 00:44:18.120
that you'd find in businesses
which might do this.

00:44:18.120 --> 00:44:21.840
Obviously, low valuations,
small value to begin with,

00:44:21.840 --> 00:44:25.450
all of those kinds of things.

00:44:25.450 --> 00:44:27.310
And maybe I'll think
of some others, but--

00:44:27.310 --> 00:44:28.500
SAURABH MADAAN: Sure.

00:44:28.500 --> 00:44:31.230
Chris Mayer, I believe, has
done sort of an updated work--

00:44:31.230 --> 00:44:31.980
CHUCK AKRE: Right.

00:44:31.980 --> 00:44:32.310
He did.

00:44:32.310 --> 00:44:33.930
SAURABH MADAAN: --in the
recent years on the same book.

00:44:33.930 --> 00:44:34.280
CHUCK AKRE: Yep.

00:44:34.280 --> 00:44:35.696
SAURABH MADAAN:
But I was curious.

00:44:35.696 --> 00:44:37.572
You have this workbench
in your portfolio--

00:44:37.572 --> 00:44:38.280
CHUCK AKRE: Yeah.

00:44:38.280 --> 00:44:38.720
Yep.

00:44:38.720 --> 00:44:39.390
SAURABH MADAAN: --the last 10%--

00:44:39.390 --> 00:44:39.720
CHUCK AKRE: Yeah.

00:44:39.720 --> 00:44:40.219
Yeah.

00:44:40.219 --> 00:44:42.540
SAURABH MADAAN: --of so
many small positions.

00:44:42.540 --> 00:44:45.120
And you mentioned this
idea of 100-baggers.

00:44:45.120 --> 00:44:45.870
CHUCK AKRE: Right.

00:44:45.870 --> 00:44:47.620
SAURABH MADAAN: So
I was just curious,

00:44:47.620 --> 00:44:50.340
what are some 100-baggers that
you see around that, you know--

00:44:50.340 --> 00:44:51.090
CHUCK AKRE: Well--

00:44:51.090 --> 00:44:52.756
SAURABH MADAAN: --you
can share with us?

00:44:52.756 --> 00:44:54.480
CHUCK AKRE: I've only
had two in my life.

00:44:54.480 --> 00:44:55.740
And I still own those two.

00:44:55.740 --> 00:44:56.531
SAURABH MADAAN: OK.

00:44:56.531 --> 00:44:59.114
CHUCK AKRE: And that's Berkshire
Hathaway and American Tower.

00:44:59.114 --> 00:45:00.030
SAURABH MADAAN: Right.

00:45:00.030 --> 00:45:03.390
CHUCK AKRE: And the
fact of the matter

00:45:03.390 --> 00:45:04.890
is, you only really need one.

00:45:04.890 --> 00:45:07.470
And I mean, and that's
a really important issue

00:45:07.470 --> 00:45:10.380
as it relates to investing,
is you really only need

00:45:10.380 --> 00:45:13.450
to have one great success.

00:45:13.450 --> 00:45:17.040
And that is, as it relates to
whatever your goals might be.

00:45:17.040 --> 00:45:23.220
And so the quest is,
for me, the search

00:45:23.220 --> 00:45:26.230
is trying to figure out what the
characteristics of those are.

00:45:26.230 --> 00:45:30.330
So if you think
about my comments,

00:45:30.330 --> 00:45:33.630
and three-legged stool,
and high return businesses,

00:45:33.630 --> 00:45:37.740
and so on, our view is
that, most of the time,

00:45:37.740 --> 00:45:39.840
you can buy these
exceptional businesses

00:45:39.840 --> 00:45:42.370
at reasonable valuations.

00:45:42.370 --> 00:45:45.780
So in today's market, you
can buy American Tower,

00:45:45.780 --> 00:45:49.160
or you can buy Moody's,
or you can buy MasterCard

00:45:49.160 --> 00:45:54.300
at probably something like 19
times next year's free cash

00:45:54.300 --> 00:45:57.290
flow, 2018.

00:45:57.290 --> 00:46:01.820
And that means an earnings
yield of 5% or 5.1%.

00:46:01.820 --> 00:46:05.030
If we're still at a 1.5%
interest rate environment,

00:46:05.030 --> 00:46:09.290
that's an attractive deal,
you know, that comparison.

00:46:09.290 --> 00:46:12.200
If the business does,
in fact, compound

00:46:12.200 --> 00:46:13.760
the free cash flow,
or book value,

00:46:13.760 --> 00:46:17.660
or whatever is appropriate for
that company, in the mid-teens

00:46:17.660 --> 00:46:21.140
and you pay in the upper
teens for it, we like to say,

00:46:21.140 --> 00:46:22.347
you'll get to heaven.

00:46:22.347 --> 00:46:23.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:23.540 --> 00:46:26.480
And you'll do so
without much risk.

00:46:26.480 --> 00:46:29.570
Periodically, the
market gives us

00:46:29.570 --> 00:46:32.690
an opportunity to buy one
of these great businesses

00:46:32.690 --> 00:46:34.130
at a discount.

00:46:34.130 --> 00:46:38.390
And then even more rarely,
it'll give us the opportunity

00:46:38.390 --> 00:46:40.380
to buy one of these at a steal.

00:46:40.380 --> 00:46:46.890
So Berkshire Hathaway, I started
buying back in the late '70s.

00:46:46.890 --> 00:46:53.250
And in the late '70s, my initial
purchases were at $105 a share,

00:46:53.250 --> 00:46:57.120
and that's the stock today, you
know, is at $250,000 a share.

00:46:57.120 --> 00:46:59.160
So that works.

00:46:59.160 --> 00:47:03.780
American Tower is, to
me, a business that

00:47:03.780 --> 00:47:06.300
is situated like Microsoft was.

00:47:06.300 --> 00:47:08.400
Microsoft was at the
intersection of the growth

00:47:08.400 --> 00:47:09.750
of the personal computer.

00:47:09.750 --> 00:47:11.244
They had the operating system.

00:47:11.244 --> 00:47:12.660
If you wanted a
personal computer,

00:47:12.660 --> 00:47:15.320
you ended up basically going
through that tollbooth,

00:47:15.320 --> 00:47:16.260
the Microsoft.

00:47:16.260 --> 00:47:20.310
And so it was a fabulously
profitable business.

00:47:20.310 --> 00:47:22.900
The growth of the wireless
communication business

00:47:22.900 --> 00:47:26.520
which, as we know, started
with 1G, and 2G, and 3G,

00:47:26.520 --> 00:47:29.400
and 4G, now they're
talking about 5G,

00:47:29.400 --> 00:47:33.630
each of those G's requires
a denser network of towers,

00:47:33.630 --> 00:47:35.970
more sophisticated
antennas, and so on.

00:47:35.970 --> 00:47:38.430
And the place they put
those are on the antennas,

00:47:38.430 --> 00:47:43.110
by and large, so that the tower
business is in that same--

00:47:43.110 --> 00:47:46.870
is in a nearly identical kind
of position that Microsoft was.

00:47:46.870 --> 00:47:50.290
And I'm not a technology guy,
so I'm already over my head.

00:47:50.290 --> 00:47:53.520
But that's a really
important notion,

00:47:53.520 --> 00:47:56.430
in terms of the exceptional
nature of a business

00:47:56.430 --> 00:47:58.980
and the ability to grow it.

00:47:58.980 --> 00:48:02.700
And their marginal
return at American Tower

00:48:02.700 --> 00:48:06.810
for an additional
tenant above about 1.2,

00:48:06.810 --> 00:48:10.710
their marginal return is
in the high 90% range.

00:48:10.710 --> 00:48:12.030
It's unbelievable.

00:48:12.030 --> 00:48:14.370
So once they put
that asset in place

00:48:14.370 --> 00:48:17.670
and they get above breakeven,
the marginal return

00:48:17.670 --> 00:48:21.540
is in the 90%
range, north of 90%.

00:48:21.540 --> 00:48:23.910
And what American
Tower has done is

00:48:23.910 --> 00:48:26.580
they now are in 15 countries.

00:48:26.580 --> 00:48:31.380
And when we started
with them in 1999,

00:48:31.380 --> 00:48:34.110
they were in the United
States, Mexico, and Brazil.

00:48:34.110 --> 00:48:36.460
Now they're in total
of 15 countries,

00:48:36.460 --> 00:48:39.360
including United States.

00:48:39.360 --> 00:48:43.800
And all of the things that
were telephony-related

00:48:43.800 --> 00:48:48.120
in the late '90s were
the hottest things

00:48:48.120 --> 00:48:51.810
since the 4th of
July firecrackers.

00:48:51.810 --> 00:48:56.190
And 2000 came, and all
of those businesses

00:48:56.190 --> 00:48:59.280
fell off the cliff,
because they were levered.

00:48:59.280 --> 00:49:01.887
Well, American Towers,
levered 16 to 1.

00:49:01.887 --> 00:49:02.970
I mean, it's unbelievable.

00:49:02.970 --> 00:49:05.640
Their huge cash flow
businesses and so on.

00:49:05.640 --> 00:49:09.870
And they had to
de-lever that company,

00:49:09.870 --> 00:49:14.010
selling assets on a distressed
basis in a declining market.

00:49:14.010 --> 00:49:18.940
And in the beginning of
2002, the stock was $5.

00:49:18.940 --> 00:49:22.790
It had gotten as high
as in the $60s in '99.

00:49:22.790 --> 00:49:26.820
Beginning of 2002, it was $5.

00:49:26.820 --> 00:49:30.570
We bought a position at $5,
and we were really proud of it.

00:49:30.570 --> 00:49:32.220
In September, it was $2.

00:49:32.220 --> 00:49:33.264
AUDIENCE: [SCOFFS]

00:49:33.264 --> 00:49:35.430
CHUCK AKRE: We got on the
plane and went see the CEO

00:49:35.430 --> 00:49:37.320
in Boston, Steve Dodge.

00:49:37.320 --> 00:49:39.180
He was the founder.

00:49:39.180 --> 00:49:44.580
And what the market
was focused on was,

00:49:44.580 --> 00:49:48.180
they had about $6 billion of
debt, but they had $200 million

00:49:48.180 --> 00:49:53.730
that came due in November
of 2003, 15 months hence.

00:49:53.730 --> 00:49:57.300
And it was payable
in cash or shares

00:49:57.300 --> 00:50:00.450
at the option of the company.

00:50:00.450 --> 00:50:03.270
They were desperately
trying to raise cash.

00:50:03.270 --> 00:50:05.580
They couldn't use their
bank lines to pay that off.

00:50:05.580 --> 00:50:09.180
You can't use the bank to pay
off somebody else's capital.

00:50:09.180 --> 00:50:11.640
And so, the lower
the price went,

00:50:11.640 --> 00:50:13.590
the more dilution an
existing shareholder

00:50:13.590 --> 00:50:17.610
was going to have if they
used shares instead of cash.

00:50:17.610 --> 00:50:24.030
And in October, the stock got
to an inter-day low of $0.60.

00:50:24.030 --> 00:50:27.720
We bought several million
shares at about $0.80.

00:50:27.720 --> 00:50:29.010
I still own mine.

00:50:29.010 --> 00:50:32.260
We have many of our
clients still own theirs.

00:50:32.260 --> 00:50:36.000
That's the other example
of a north of 100-bagger.

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:38.430
What was interesting was
that the business itself

00:50:38.430 --> 00:50:43.500
was a terrific business
masked by a bad balance sheet.

00:50:43.500 --> 00:50:46.290
And you had great
people working hard

00:50:46.290 --> 00:50:47.940
to get it straightened
out, to preserve

00:50:47.940 --> 00:50:51.000
their own investment, their
own foundations, and that sort

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:52.710
of stuff.

00:50:52.710 --> 00:50:56.040
And it was just, so I
think to myself, well,

00:50:56.040 --> 00:50:59.190
did I make a mistake by not
really putting a lot of money

00:50:59.190 --> 00:50:59.910
to work?

00:50:59.910 --> 00:51:01.350
I was very timid.

00:51:01.350 --> 00:51:03.960
If I say we bought a few
million shares at $0.80,

00:51:03.960 --> 00:51:06.760
that's not a lot of money.

00:51:06.760 --> 00:51:09.122
And so, if I'd been
more confident,

00:51:09.122 --> 00:51:10.830
I would have put a
lot of money in there,

00:51:10.830 --> 00:51:14.580
and I'd be fighting with
Warren Buffett for the place

00:51:14.580 --> 00:51:16.506
on that list, you know?

00:51:16.506 --> 00:51:18.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:18.240 --> 00:51:20.030
But you get the idea.

00:51:20.030 --> 00:51:23.010
So the point is that,
periodically, you

00:51:23.010 --> 00:51:26.340
get a chance to buy one of these
great businesses at a bargain,

00:51:26.340 --> 00:51:30.195
and even, in a rare
opportunity, at just a steal.

00:51:30.195 --> 00:51:31.320
SAURABH MADAAN: Yes, Chuck.

00:51:31.320 --> 00:51:34.740
I have one final
question for you.

00:51:34.740 --> 00:51:36.660
There was a 2006
interview of yours

00:51:36.660 --> 00:51:37.910
that I was mentioning to you--

00:51:37.910 --> 00:51:38.130
CHUCK AKRE: Yeah.

00:51:38.130 --> 00:51:40.680
SAURABH MADAAN: --before
we began the conversation.

00:51:40.680 --> 00:51:43.482
And Penn National Gaming, I
think, was one of the stocks--

00:51:43.482 --> 00:51:44.190
CHUCK AKRE: Yeah.

00:51:44.190 --> 00:51:46.680
SAURABH MADAAN: --that was
a big part of your portfolio

00:51:46.680 --> 00:51:51.250
at that time, and so was
this company called Markel.

00:51:51.250 --> 00:51:54.090
So I remember the stock
price from that interview

00:51:54.090 --> 00:51:57.060
because it was 4-4-4.

00:51:57.060 --> 00:51:58.885
And today, it's roughly--

00:51:58.885 --> 00:51:59.760
CHUCK AKRE: 9-9-9.

00:51:59.760 --> 00:52:00.634
SAURABH MADAAN: Yeah.

00:52:00.634 --> 00:52:02.910
It's slightly more than double.

00:52:02.910 --> 00:52:04.664
But it's also been
over 11 years.

00:52:04.664 --> 00:52:05.330
CHUCK AKRE: Yes.

00:52:05.330 --> 00:52:06.705
SAURABH MADAAN:
So the reason I'm

00:52:06.705 --> 00:52:08.970
asking is, does there
come a point, even

00:52:08.970 --> 00:52:11.430
in the life of a
good compounder,

00:52:11.430 --> 00:52:15.510
where the valuations are
becoming optimistic enough,

00:52:15.510 --> 00:52:18.540
and the future rates of
returns that you can see

00:52:18.540 --> 00:52:22.740
are low, where one should
maybe rotate or move

00:52:22.740 --> 00:52:24.160
from one position to another.

00:52:24.160 --> 00:52:28.212
How do you think about
selling, in other words?

00:52:28.212 --> 00:52:29.670
CHUCK AKRE: Well,
one side of that.

00:52:29.670 --> 00:52:32.160
I think the most
difficult thing to do

00:52:32.160 --> 00:52:36.790
in our business is to not sell
if you're a long-term investor.

00:52:36.790 --> 00:52:41.760
And that is, the ones
that are really great

00:52:41.760 --> 00:52:43.980
have been hard for
me to identify.

00:52:43.980 --> 00:52:48.210
It's taken me a long time to
understand how good the ones

00:52:48.210 --> 00:52:50.460
are that are really good.

00:52:50.460 --> 00:52:57.400
And almost everybody has less
time in the market than I do.

00:52:57.400 --> 00:53:00.510
But for those who have fewer
years experience, you know,

00:53:00.510 --> 00:53:03.610
if you get a
disappointing quarter

00:53:03.610 --> 00:53:08.190
or you get something like that,
temptation is often the sell.

00:53:08.190 --> 00:53:10.140
And if you've got
a really great one,

00:53:10.140 --> 00:53:12.120
that's probably a bad decision.

00:53:12.120 --> 00:53:14.490
Doesn't mean you can't
lighten up a little bit,

00:53:14.490 --> 00:53:16.710
and try to time it
and buy some more.

00:53:16.710 --> 00:53:18.460
We don't do that very well.

00:53:18.460 --> 00:53:21.080
So we try not to
fool around with.

00:53:21.080 --> 00:53:25.080
In the case of
Markel, like Enstar,

00:53:25.080 --> 00:53:27.590
they'd had a record of 20
years of compounding book

00:53:27.590 --> 00:53:29.400
value per share.

00:53:29.400 --> 00:53:32.220
In 2006, that was,
like, 20% a year.

00:53:32.220 --> 00:53:34.710
And so like Enstar, which
was three times book when

00:53:34.710 --> 00:53:36.780
I bought it, Markel
got to the point

00:53:36.780 --> 00:53:39.630
where it was 2 and 1/2 times
book or something like that.

00:53:39.630 --> 00:53:42.000
And the fact that
I've only doubled

00:53:42.000 --> 00:53:48.990
my money in 10 years, so 7%
return, is a result of that.

00:53:48.990 --> 00:53:52.697
By paying a valuation, which,
in hindsight, was too high,

00:53:52.697 --> 00:53:54.780
because the rate at which
they could compound book

00:53:54.780 --> 00:53:58.470
was less than I had
imagined it might be.

00:53:58.470 --> 00:54:01.200
Part of that backdrop
is this whole issue

00:54:01.200 --> 00:54:04.140
of this 36-year secular
decline in rates.

00:54:04.140 --> 00:54:08.910
All businesses have done less
well over the last 5 or 10

00:54:08.910 --> 00:54:11.120
years because of the
decline in rates,

00:54:11.120 --> 00:54:13.230
and Markel is an example.

00:54:13.230 --> 00:54:17.940
And they've now, in
my mind, fully adopted

00:54:17.940 --> 00:54:21.270
the Berkshire model of creating
a business inside the holding

00:54:21.270 --> 00:54:23.640
company that's completely
away from insurance.

00:54:23.640 --> 00:54:25.360
They call it Markel Ventures.

00:54:25.360 --> 00:54:28.140
Got $1.2 billion in revenue,
as you said, about $130 million

00:54:28.140 --> 00:54:29.340
in EBITDA.

00:54:29.340 --> 00:54:32.310
So it's roughly at 10
times EBITDA margin.

00:54:32.310 --> 00:54:35.220
And that will give
them the flexibility

00:54:35.220 --> 00:54:38.370
of being able to put capital
to work, other than simply

00:54:38.370 --> 00:54:42.360
in a passive portfolio, rather
in an insurance business when

00:54:42.360 --> 00:54:44.310
rates aren't attractive to them.

00:54:44.310 --> 00:54:46.980
And they're one of the very
small number of insurance

00:54:46.980 --> 00:54:49.890
companies that have the
discipline of only putting

00:54:49.890 --> 00:54:54.960
money to work when
their expected return is

00:54:54.960 --> 00:54:57.199
a positive combined ratio.

